default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommunity transport 
defaultcan be 
defaulta lifeline in both rural and urban areas. It takes disabled people t
defaulto work, children to school, sick people to healthcare and older people to the shops. It runs local bus routes and provides transport for a wide range of clubs, voluntary bodies and care homes. People shape the services they want and comm
defaultunity transport mak
defaultes it happen.
default&#xa0;default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommunity Transport schemes serving the most remote corners of the country, or schemes working in partnership with other local services like youth clubs or care homes, can really make a huge difference to people who use them. Community Transport is part of
default the Transport mix in isolated communities but not the sole 
defaultsolution to passenger transport
default.
default&#xa0;default4.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCentral Government and Local Authorities are unrealistic if they expect volunteer run community transport projects to fill gaps left by deep bus cuts. Research fr
defaultom the Community Transport Association has shown that community transport can only fill between 10 to 15 per cent
default of former supported transport provision
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe integration of services and pooling for budgets, at both local and national levels, can ensure t
defaulthat public money is made to work harder. Some local authorities have already made savings by integrating the way they contract public bus services, school buses and social services transport. Partnerships between councils, operators and big institutions li
defaultke hospitals and universities have had good results. Taxi buses, NHS transport, travel schemes for post 16 students and social enterprises all have a part to play. In some cases core routes linking towns are met by demand response village services at reque
defaultst stops. 
default&#xa0;
default4.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA ‘Total Transport’ solution for areas affected by cuts to services which would bring together all transport provision in an area
default such as private operators, council run services, 
defaulth
defaultospital 
defaultt
defaultransport
default and social services.
default&#xa0;
default4.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommunity Rail Partnersh
defaultips play
default an important 
defaultrole in
default providing transport for isolated communities.
default 
defaultThe case for new or reopened connections is increasingly strong, with demand for rail now at its highest level since before the Second World War, despite the network being 
defaultconsiderably smaller than then. Despite the growing case for these connections, there is no clear process in the rail industry for this to happen and many local authorities lack the capacity or skills to progress schemes themselves. Some new lines and stat
defaultions have been built, however, and demand on these new lines and stations has usually been higher than forecast.
